By the time you hit mid-30's, you'll discover that warriors don't deal as much damage as the other classes.  What warriors are good at, however, is soaking damage.  A good damage/delay weapon is needed for the times when you're fighting in small groups or in melee groups.<br>
<br>
But if you group up with casters, max up your AC instead.  There's a few weapons that give an AC bonus ... very useful in soaking up damage.<br>
<br>
On the other hand ... if you want to hit well, the trick is in increasing your &quot;ATK&quot; rating ... which means getting more strength.<br>
<br>
I've never heard of any theories about Dex increasing accuracy ... and while that sounds right, Verant never seemed to do anything right.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubjond.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bjond</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/14/01 7:02:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm43.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=35.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Uh, no ..</span><hr size=1> .. dexterity and strength have zero effect on hits or misses.  I spent weeks parsing data with and without shaman dex, agi, and str buffs to learn that one.  Stamina has a slight effect, but only when your sta-bar is zeroed (reduces hit chance).  I once believed dex mattered, too.  I believed it so much that my old warior plowed tons of his starting points into dex.  That was a pretty big blunder, but I already had him in the 40's before I figured that out.<br>
<br>
What dex does do is increase the chance of a &quot;proc&quot; very slightly and also increases the speed at which you learn weapon skills: dex+max(int,wis) determines weapon skill advancement rate.  What str does is increase the chance of a harder hit (you'll hit closer to maximum) and it also increases the maximum hit.  The gain is slight, perhaps 2 or 3 points for +25 str, but it's there.  If you have to pick one buff, make it STR if your STA is over 100 and STA if it's under.  If I could make my old warrior over, I'd have made sure AGI was 85+, then plowed all the other points into STA.  If I had any left, I'd use them on STR.<br>
<br>
The thing that effects hit/miss most is the weapon skill, the critter's AC, and the difference in level between you and your target.  You'll find that as you level up, you miss quite a bit less.  Your skill will be a lot higher and you'll be hunting relatively lower-level critters than you would hunt as a newbie.<br>
<br>
Also, while warriors aren't quite the top damage machines under level 50, post 50 they do extremely well -- almost as good as a monk.  There's never a level where any class can tank better than a warrior.  The top warriors hype their HP and AC over just about everything else.  Warrior AC/HP + Cleric CH == happy group.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
BTW, this is probably the only time I'll post on stats, since just about everyone has a die-hard opinion on them that they'll defend to the death -- mostly formed like this: &quot;but, it just makes sense that dex would improve to-hit chance&quot;.  All I can say is build your character in the way that feels right to you.  This is only what I've learned from my own in-game testing. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubraellarth.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Braellarth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/14/01 9:17:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm43.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=35.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Uh, no ..</span><hr size=1> &lt;ooc<br>
